<font color="#FF0000">TOUGH ? REQUIRES REAL THOUGHT</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct 24  2:22:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW, when I think of our troops, I agree that we need to keep mines.  Paul, when I think of the kids who will come along later, I tend to agree that we need to ban these weapons.  <br><br>
We are now using them in Korea, at the DMZ.  Are we using them in Bosnia?  I don't know.  <br><br>
I was in First Marine Division's hospital when some Korean soldiers came in after having tripped a booby trap.  One had a bed sprind laying against his fractured femur (as seen on the x-ray).  Pretty ugly.  <br><br>
I had a friend who went through Recondo school in South Vietnam, where they were taught about explosives.  But we didn't get into it.  We were more into emergency medicine.<br><br>
With that bit of waffling, let me say that I hope that our techniques of warfare are such that we don't again get into a situation where these measures will be necessary.  <br><br>
Now, let me rephrase the question:  Are there methods developed in the last 25 years which would make these land mines obsolete?  <br><br>
One other question: Is it better to openly declare that we cannot abide by this treaty, state the reasons, and also state that we will do all within our power to not use these weapons and to make them so that they self-destruct (not explosively, one hopes) after a certain amount of time?  I understand that this is happening.<br><br>
One final thought:  if we were to sign this treaty, would we abide by it?<br><br>
I have been thinking with my fingers here, but I &quot;think&quot; I would prefer us to be openly against the treaty than to say we would do it, and then break our word--or not break our word and risk our soldier's lives.<br><br>
With that said, let's look at the real cause of the problem, the indescriminant mining of populated areas with the intent of harming the local population, not the soldiers.  In other words, some of the problem can be considered terrorist tactics against a local population.
